The City School District of New Rochelle added 6 new photos.
June 15 at 10:59 PM ·

It was great day here in Westchester County today. After all, it was officially Michael Hilderbrand Day.
The Principal of Trinity Elementary School was celebrated on the marquee outside the Westchester County Center.
Indeed, this was just the final of four fantastic days. Over the past week or so, there were also days named for three other elementary school principals -- Michael Galland of Columbus, Anthony Bambrola of George M. Davis Jr. and Franco Miele of William B. Ward.
The four were honored as "Great Educators" at the Boys and Girls Club of New Rochelle's "Be Great" gala, held virtually recently. That was enough for the The Westchester County Board of Legislators to declare four days in their honor.
Congratulations! This was well deserved by all!
Learn more about the gala here:
https://begreat.onlinegalas.com/?q=be-great-2020-live.html

post_text:
Here's how they did it.
The students in the annual Poetry Project at New Rochelle High School faced an unprecedented challenge as they prepared to create movies inspired by poems they studied.
COVID-19 closed the schools before movie-making day. So they created their five short movies under stay-at-home orders.
Check out this documentary, Behind the Scenes, to see how they problem-solved and learned to respond to the unexpected with innovation and imagination.
The films are just part of the At Home Artsfest the NRHS art department will present from 3 p.m. to 7 p.m. Wednesday. Watch it all at this link:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tXvhw7Ib0Xw&feature=youtu.be

The City School District of New Rochelle added 6 new photos — at New Rochelle High School.
May 20 at 6:25 PM · New Rochelle, NY ·

Members of the Class of 2020 picked up their signs today to proudly display on their lawns. In the teachers' parking lot at New Rochelle High School, each senior or family drove up to a checkpoint, then proceeded to where staff and students placed the signs in the trunk.
"It was great to see the smiles on the students' faces as they picked up their signs and we cheered them on," said Interim Assistant Principal Rachel Cornelius.
They handed out 422 signs today.
Seniors who did not have a chance to pick one up today can get them at the school tomorrow from 9 a.m. to 1 p.m.
Look for them around the city.
Congratulations, seniors!
#classof2020

April 7 at 12:50 PM · New Rochelle, NY ·

Our teachers and other staff members are showing how a community stays together even when we're physically apart.
Today, they held two teachers parades, driving past students' homes to lift spirits and show the students they are missed.
During the school closure - now extending through April 27 per directive of the Governor - classes are conducted on line.
The parades add the in-person smiles and cheers, while maintaining social distance.
“Kids are saying they’re missing the teachers, the teachers miss the students," said Renee Bartee, a pre-kindergarten teacher at Henry Barnard Early Childhood Center who organized the parade starting there. "We thought we would show them that we’re thinking… More

post_text:
More great news from the Science Research Program at New Rochelle High School. Nine of the students in the program have been chosen as finalists in the annual GENIUS Olympiad, an international high school competition that promotes a global understanding of environmental issues and the achievement of sustainability through basic science, arts, creative writing, engineering, design, and business development.

The NRHS students chosen are:

Akshara Koottala
Sarah Athir
Fatima Gonzalez
Rachel Fox
Rachel Rivera
Brittney Benjamin
Sara Fryxell
Yaffa Segal
Hayden Roberge

"I am so proud of all of our finalists!" said program director Jeff Wuebber. "They have all worked so hard and I'm so happy to see that hard work recognized! These students were selected among submissions of students from seventy-two countries!"

Congratulations to all!

Learn more about the GENIUS Olympiad, including the complete list of finalists from around the world, here:

The City School District of New Rochelle added 5 new photos — in New Rochelle, New York.
March 16 at 1:14 PM · New Rochelle, NY ·

Three new locations opened today in the City School District of New Rochelle's food support initiative. While the schools are closed by the COVID-19 crisis, the District has joined with community organizations to provide food for students who rely on the school day for a is providing meals to students who generally rely on the school day for some meals.
The new sites are Trinity and Columbus elementary schools and City Park.
For a complete list, see below.
Thank you to Westchester Community Action Program, Feeding Westchester and the New Rochelle Municipal Housing Authority for helping out in this challenging time.

● New Rochelle High School House IV parking lot 9:00am – 1:00pm
● 95 Lincoln (WESTCOP) 9:00am – 4:00pm (Extended hours)
● 345 Main Street (New Rochelle Housing Authority) 9:00am – 4:00pm (Extended hours)
● Trinity Elementary School from 9:00am to noon
● Columbus Elementary School from 9:00am to noon
● City Park from 9:00am – 4:00pm (Extended hours)

Superintendent Dr. Laura Feijóo (left) and Board of Education President Amy Moselhi discuss the state's closure of three City School District of New Rochelle schools for two weeks.
New Rochelle High School, Albert Leonard Middle School and William B. Ward Elementary School will be closed from tomorrow, March 11, through March 25. They are in a containment area, within a mile of Young Israel of New Rochelle. (The Alternative Campus School will also close during that time as it is a program of the high school.)

post_text:
Superintendent Dr. Laura Feijóo sent the District's plan for Coronavirus COVID-19 today. Here is the message with the plan:

Dear parents, guardians and community,

Please see attached the City School District of New Rochelle’s plan for addressing the Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) concern. This plan will govern our management of the District unless and until we receive further guidance from the New York State Education Department or Westchester County Department of Health.

The plan is founded on best practices with input from our central administration team, district physician, building principals, director of special education and district counsel. We appreciate that NYSED and WCDOH are under tremendous pressure to respond to multiple inquiries from our neighboring districts and that is why we have taken the lead.

post_text:
The cast of the upcoming TheatreWorks production of Head Over Heels were treated to a rare opportunity today when Michael Mayer, the Tony-award winning director who helmed the play on Broadway in 2018 teleconferenced in to chat with them.
Mayer told the students that the show is "a beautiful example of how love is love is love and there are all sorts of ways for people to love each other."
Mayer connected with them thanks to Melissa Panszi Riebe, President of the Albert Leonard Middle School PTA, who is friends with director.

The Museum of Arts & Culture in House IV of New Rochelle High School will hold a reception Saturday, Jan. 18, noon-4 p.m., for an exhibition of work by artist-in-residence Susan Luss.
She has also created works that fill windows near the gallery with color to create art with sunlight.
Luss has been working with PAVE Visual Arts 1,2,3 and 2D and 3D Advanced Placement classes. Students' work around the gallery and in the House IV cafeteria will complement Luss's works. They also created the sun-oriented works, as well as an exhibition of found objects on display in the smaller gallery space near the museum.
Here are some scenes of the works and the students preparing.

The City School District of New Rochelle added 8 new photos — at New Rochelle Public Library.
January 12 at 12:47 PM · New Rochelle, NY ·

The lobby of the New Rochelle Public Library was filled with the fruits of scientific research in the first annual Science Research Fair for students in grades 4 through 8.
Students presented the results of their investigations similar to the way research is conducted in New Rochelle High School's Science Research Program.
Topics included Piaget's Theory of Conservation, the connection between sunlight and reducing the risk of myopia and the challenges presented by autism.
The fair was organized by the Foundation for Science Research in New Rochelle. Thank you to the New Rochelle Fund for Educational Excellence for the support provided and the New Rochelle Public Library for hosting.

post_text:
Dr. Caren Baruch-Feldman, a Scarsdale-based psychologist and author of the book The Grit Guide for Teens, will talk with parents on the topic of "Reducing Stress in Children and Teens" at the Jan. 13 meeting of New Rochelle SEPTA.
The meeting, which is open to all, will begin at 7:30 p.m. in room 207 of New Rochelle High School, 265 Clove Road.
Dr. Baruch-Feldman “uses Cognitive Behavioral Therapy to help children and adults with depression, anxiety, stress, ADHD and weight loss,” reads her website. She serves as a school psychologist in Westchester and for many years was Camp Psychologist at Camp Ramah in Nyack.
“Caren is an expert in conducting psycho-educational evaluations for children experiencing school-related difficulties,” according to her website. “She has also trained hundreds of teachers, parents, children and health care professionals giving workshops and lectures throughout the country.”

The City School District of New Rochelle added 4 new photos — in New Rochelle, New York.
December 19, 2019 at 6:28 PM · New Rochelle, NY ·

The state champion Huguenots football team was celebrated today, along with the cheerleaders and pep band, in a rally in New Rochelle High School's Whitney M. Young Jr. Auditorium.
"You brought the community, once again, to a new level," District Assistant Superintendent for Support Services Dr. Anthony Bongo told them.
The NRHS Huguenots won the Class AA state championship game in Syracuse on Nov. 30, shutting out McQuaid Jesuit High School of Rochester 28-0.
Others praising the team included New York State Sen. Andrea Stewart-Cousins, State Assemblywoman Amy Paulin, Interim Principal Joseph Starvaggi and Director of Athletics Steve Young.

December 18, 2019 at 1:46 AM ·

New Rochelle's Special Olympians were celebrated by the New Rochelle Board of Education with a resolution Tuesday evening.
Their ranks have grown so much they have now formed two teams - the purple and the white - in the region's Pioneers league.
They played soccer against Port Chester here in New Rochelle last Wednesday, kicking off a season that lasts months and gives them the opportunity to play several different sports.
Superintendent Dr. Laura Feijóo gave them certificates at the meeting Tuesday in the Linda E. Kelly Theater in New Rochelle High School.
Here's to a great season, New Rochelle Pioneers! We're rooting for you!

December 11, 2019 at 3:47 PM · New Rochelle, NY ·

A mayor, an author, college administrators and a former head of the National Urban League discussed position papers written by five New Rochelle High School students in the annual Civics Symposium. It was presented by the New Rochelle Fund for Educational Excellence and took place Tuesday in the Linda E. Kelly Theater.
The panelists were:
• Hugh Price, former President and Chief Executive of the National Urban League.
• Noam Bramson, New Rochelle Mayor.
• Alex Eodice, Iona College philosophy professor and philosophy department chairman.
• Yadira Ramos-Herbert, New Rochelle City Council member-elect and Dean of Students at Columbia Law School.
• Joe Klein, journalist author of Primary Colors.

Here are some scenes.

The annual holiday "Season of Light" show returns to the New Rochelle High School planetarium this month.
The show explores why people have been fascinated with lighting the December darkness since ancient times. It looks at the astronomical explanations of seasonal traditions such as the "Star of Bethlehem."
Shows are free. No reservations required, but please get there on time. Once the show starts, no one can enter. (Doors open 15 minutes before showtime.)

Dates:
Saturday, Dec. 14 at 2 and 4 p.m.
Monday, Dec. 16 at 7 p.m.
Wednesday, Dec. 18 at 7 p.m.

We're incredibly grateful to actor John Amos (of "Good Times," "Roots" and "Coming to America") who visited William B. Ward Elementary School today. He read a children's book, "A World Without Color," which he wrote in a collaboration with Ward teacher Lisa Figaro.
Thank you News 12 Westchester for stopping by to put together this report on it!

November 24, 2019 at 1:57 PM ·

New Rochelle High School's Anthony Stirpe gave a presentation on his innovative, multi-media poetry project in Baltimore this weekend.
The project is so popular, the English teaacher has given presentations on it around the country -- and most recently, in Azerbaijan's capital city of Baku.
This weekend, he was presenting his project at the National Council of Teachers of English.

The Huguenots are going back to the Dome!!! They just beat Shenendehowa 24-17 in the Class AA semifinals.
They’ll go on to the state championship at the Carrier Dome in Syracuse on Dec. 1.
Here’s what the scene was like when it happened.
Great job, team!

Barnard Early Childhood Center turned purple for World Pancreatic Cancer Day, Nov. 21.
Students and staff wore purple to help raise awareness of the world’s toughest cancer. Pancreatic cancer has the lowest survival rate among all major cancers with a survival rate of only 9 percent.
This is the sixth year Barnard School has turned purple to help raise awareness of this disease.
Tara Knebel, Barnard Kindergarten Special Education teacher, lost her mom to pancreatic cancer more than 10 years ago and has joined with Barnard School and the New Rochelle community to raise awareness and research funds for pancreatic cancer.
Mrs. Knebel organizes the Westchester Pancreatic Cancer Research Walk every year, with the support and help of many New Rochelle teachers throughout the district. This year's walk will take place on Sunday, April 26th, 2020 at Rye Playland

It’s Game Day!
The Huguenots' state semifinal game is just four hours from now in Middletown. They'll battle Shenendehowa to get to Syracuse for the state Class AA Championship next weekend.
Kickoff today is 6 p.m. at Middletown High School, 30 Gardner Extension Ave., Middletown.
Good luck Huguenots! For live updates, follow @NewRochelleED on Twitter.
